docs.abstract: Mr. Schultz, the former chief executive of Starbucks, was greeted by about 40 protesters at an event after saying he would consider running for president as an independent.
docs.snippet: Mr. Schultz, the former chief executive of Starbucks, was greeted by about 40 protesters at an event after saying he would consider running for president as an independent.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — As cars and pedestrians passed by during the evening rush on Thursday, Paula Harper-Christensen, a retired teacher, smiled and waved her sign with an upside-down Starbucks mermaid. “Don’t spill our chance,” the text said under the logo. Susan Glicksberg’s protest placard was more blunt: “Do Not Run!”

headline.main: Howard Schultz Draws Protesters in His Hometown, Seattle

docs.abstract: The art of inspiring online donors is very much about timing: It’s about having a moment in the national spotlight — and then capitalizing on it. A looming deadline helps, too.
docs.snippet: The art of inspiring online donors is very much about timing: It’s about having a moment in the national spotlight — and then capitalizing on it. A looming deadline helps, too.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the 2020 race for the White House, small donors are expected to play a more significant role than ever before. With so many Democratic candidates running, and only so much money to go around, whom small donors choose to support will determine in part which contenders will have the cash to compete — and who will not.

headline.main: 6 Days When 2020 Democratic Hopefuls Scored With Small Donors
headline.print_headline: How 6 Democrats Connected With Small Donors (Timing Helped)

docs.abstract: The Virginia governor was said to be planning to hire a private investigator to help clear his name, as his relationship with his lieutenant governor is strained.
docs.snippet: The Virginia governor was said to be planning to hire a private investigator to help clear his name, as his relationship with his lieutenant governor is strained.
docs.lead_paragraph: RICHMOND, Va. — The besieged Democratic governor of Virginia, Ralph Northam, began to emerge from his defensive crouch on Tuesday, and signaled through his diminished corps of allies that he believed he could remain in office and, perhaps, prove that he did not appear in a racist photograph more than 30 years ago.

headline.main: Ralph Northam Seeks Signs of Support as Crisis Strains Virginia Leadership
headline.print_headline: Virginia Governor, Digging In, May Hire Detective to Rebut Photo

docs.abstract: Mr. Biden responded to criticism over his handling of Anita Hill’s 1991 testimony. Here are our observations from the show.
docs.snippet: Mr. Biden responded to criticism over his handling of Anita Hill’s 1991 testimony. Here are our observations from the show.
docs.lead_paragraph: Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. sat down with “The View” for his first extended interview since announcing his third run for president on Thursday. The show, hosted by an all-female panel, was an interesting choice of venue for the 76-year-old Democrat: Mr. Biden entered the race weeks after several women came forward to say his interactions with them had made them uncomfortable, and he is facing a fresh round of criticism for his treatment of Anita Hill during the 1991 confirmation hearings of Justice Clarence Thomas.

headline.main: Recap and Analysis: Joe Biden’s Visit to ‘The View’

byline.original: By Matt Flegenheimer, Sydney Ember and Alexander Burns
